<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1281,1776]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1389,1415]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Habitat.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3697307552" country="Paraguay" location="Nothing" municipality="Villarrica" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" specimenCount="1">
Knowledge regarding 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Nieser &amp; Alkins-Koo" authorityYear="1991" box="[552,655,1390,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">
<emphasis box="[552,655,1390,1416]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. celeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based only on the 
<typeStatus box="[884,932,1390,1416]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">type</typeStatus>
series from 
<collectingCountry box="[1068,1172,1390,1416]" name="Paraguay" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
(Nieser 1994). 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:D7768787FFAD0D221ADBFBA81033F911:5A00604AFFAD0D221F0CFAF21183FA69" box="[1344,1436,1390,1416]" country="Paraguay" municipality="Villarrica" name="Nothing" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Nothing</location>
is known about its habitat associations except that it was found in a marsh in 
<collectingMunicipality box="[1015,1121,1426,1452]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Villarrica</collectingMunicipality>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Drake, C. J. &amp; Harris, H. M." box="[1135,1372,1426,1452]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" pagination="179 - 240" refId="ref49270" refString="Drake, C. J. &amp; Harris, H. M. (1934) The Gerrinae of the Western Hemisphere (Hemiptera). Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 23, 179 - 240." type="journal article" year="1934">Drake &amp; Harris 1934</bibRefCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1281,1776]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">
At the INR, this species was collected from a single locality: a shaded roadside ditch with floating vegetation at the margins (
<figureCitation box="[324,405,1498,1524]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1175,1199]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1151]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1435,181,1151]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. 14, Habitat of Neogerris celeris at Reserva Privada Don Luis in roadside ditches (San Ignacio RS). 15–16, Habitat of Ovatametra obesa at Camping Monterrey (San Ignacio RS): 15, in marshes; 16, in flood-prone areas. 17, Habitat of Curicta granulosa at Lobo Cuá Stream (Laguna Iberá RS)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332134/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="467" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1281,1776]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,313,1534,1560]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Remarks.</emphasis>
The cosmopolitan genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1913" box="[607,719,1535,1560]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[607,719,1535,1560]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Neogerris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
currently comprises 13 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Damgaard, J. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Weir, T. A. &amp; Zettel, H." box="[1100,1359,1534,1560]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" pagination="251 - 281" refId="ref48146" refString="Damgaard, J., Moreira, F. F. F., Weir, T. A. &amp; Zettel, H. (2014) Molecular phylogeny of the pond skaters (Gerrinae), discussion of the fossil record and a checklist of species assigned to the subfamily. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, 45, 251 - 281. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1876312 X- 44042105" type="journal article" year="2014">
Damgaard 
<emphasis box="[1229,1288,1534,1560]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Until now, only 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[270,394,1570,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lubricus">
<emphasis box="[270,394,1570,1596]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. lubricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had been recorded from Argentina (
<bibRefCitation author="Coscaron, M. C." box="[803,981,1570,1596]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" pagination="1 - 432" refId="ref47917" refString="Coscaron, M. C. (2017) A catalogue of the Heteroptera (Hemiptera) or true bugs of Argentina. Zootaxa, 4295 (1), 1 - 432. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4295.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Coscarón 2017</bibRefCitation>
). The collection of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Nieser &amp; Alkins-Koo" authorityYear="1991" box="[1208,1315,1570,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">
<emphasis box="[1208,1315,1570,1596]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. celeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from INR extends the known range of this species from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[764,868,1606,1632]" name="Paraguay" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
to northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1046,1157,1606,1632]" name="Argentina" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. Nieser (1994) restricted the geographical distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Nieser &amp; Alkins-Koo" authorityYear="1991" box="[513,621,1642,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">
<emphasis box="[513,621,1642,1668]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. celeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to its type-locality in 
<collectingCountry box="[871,975,1642,1668]" name="Paraguay" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
as this species can be misidentified with 
<taxonomicName authority="(White, 1879)" baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[151,399,1678,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lotus">
<emphasis box="[151,237,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. lotus</emphasis>
(White, 1879)
</taxonomicName>
due to variations in the pronotum length. Therefore, records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Nieser &amp; Alkins-Koo" authorityYear="1991" box="[1098,1205,1678,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">
<emphasis box="[1098,1205,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. celeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other countries are not considered here. The posterior margin of abdominal tergum VIII, which is deeply notched in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Nieser &amp; Alkins-Koo" authorityYear="1991" box="[1289,1394,1714,1740]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">
<emphasis box="[1289,1394,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. celeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but hardly notched in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[348,469,1750,1776]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Neogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lubricus">
<emphasis box="[348,469,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">N. lubricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, readily differentiates the males of these two species.
</paragraph>
